title: diegr
text: package contains built-datasets. Due nature experiment size data, small section serves demonstration implemented functions possible reconstruct real signal specific sensor subject . Details experiment original data comes can found Madetko-Alster col., 2025.

title: diegr
text: brain signal originally measured 256-channel HydroCel Geodesic Sensor Net sampling frequency 250 Hz. Example dataset contains amplitude values 204 selected channels 50 time points (stimulus time point 10) 2 representative subjects (one healthy control, one patient). 50 epochs per subject, 14 (15, respectively) selected. data organized data frame following columns: time: Number time point. Number 10 indicates time stimulus (0 ms), interval two time points corresponds 4 ms (sampling frequency 250 Hz). signal: HD-EEG signal amplitude (microvolts). epoch: Epoch number (14 epochs subject one, 15 epochs subject two). sensor: Sensor label (labeling corresponds Geodesic Sensor Net Technical Manual, 2024). subject: Subject ID (1 - representative healthy control subject, 2 - representative patient subject).

title: diegr
text: Cartesian coordinates HD-EEG sensor positions 3D space scalp surface projection 2D space according 256-channel HydroCel Geodesic Sensor Net average template montage. data organized list following elements: D2: tibble coordinates labels sensors 2D. D3: tibble coordinates labels sensors 3D. ROI:vector region interest (ROI) assignment sensor (“central”, “frontal”, “occipital”, “parietal” “temporal” according brain regions “face” face area). Sensors labeled according Geodesic Sensor Net Technical Manual, 2024. Axis orientation (3D): - x: left (-) right (+); - y: posterior (-) anterior (+); - z: inferior (-) superior (+).

title: diegr
text: response time values individual experiment epochs 2 representative subjects (one patient, one healthy control group). epochs subjects correspond sample dataset epochdata. data organized data frame following columns: subject: Subject ID (1 - representative healthy control subject, 2 - representative patient subject). epoch: Epoch number (14 epochs subject one, 15 epochs subject two). RT: Response time ms.

title: diegr
text: package assumes input data already preprocessed (artifact removal, independent component analysis - ICA, segmentation, …), may still contain outliers excluded specific statistical analyses. useful tool outliers detection interactive plot boxplots amplitudes (boxplot_epoch()) response times (boxplot_rt()) individual epochs. plotly output makes easy determine epoch number outliers come additionally allows editing output image layout. also interactive graph amplitudes individual epochs (without) average plotted (interactive_waveforms()). function can also used compare signals across different experimental levels (e.g., sensor, subject, group, condition) specified level argument. Outlier epochs can easily detected using hover text plotly output. case , outlier epoch 14. results can supported computationally outliers_epoch() function, allows evaluation outliers using one three criteria (interquartile range - IQR, percentile approach Hampel filter). output function table containing epoch IDs number time points epochs evaluated outliers (according chosen criteria) unique combinations input variables (e.g. group, subject, sensor). results correspond findings boxplot_epoch() - subject 1, epoch 14 evaluated outlier 50 time points. Analogously function boxplot_epoch(), function boxplot_subject() works identify outliers subject level.
code: # The function for interactive boxplot of signal assumes  # pre-filtered data input # example: subject 1 and channel E34 in time points from 10 to 20 subdata <- epochdata |>   pick_data(subject_rg = 1, sensor_rg = "E34") boxplot_epoch(subdata, amplitude = "signal", time_lim = 10:20)  # customizing the output title and axis labels using |> operator p1 <- boxplot_epoch(subdata, amplitude = "signal", time_lim = 10:20) p1 |> plotly::layout(xaxis = list(title = ""),                      yaxis = list(title = "Amplitude"),                      title = list(text = "Outlier detection for subject 1 and channel E34",                                   font = list(size = 11, color = "darkblue"))                      ) # note: the output is not plotted to reduce the vignette file size # Example: outlier detection for both subjects and channel E34 using IQR method # The column in which we are looking for outliers is specified by the `amplitude` argument epochdata |>   pick_data(sensor_rg = "E34") |> outliers_epoch(amplitude = "signal", method = "iqr")

title: diegr
text: main focus package interactive visualization animation HD-EEG data. often requires first baseline correcting data averaging signal across epochs, sensors/time points, subjects. baseline correction amplitude enabled function baseline_correction(). first release package, commonly used absolute correction (type = "absolute"), subtracts mean base_int, available. calculation average signal can performed using function compute_mean(), computes pointwise standard/weighted jackknife (leave one ) mean signal different levels. addition mean , function also calculates boundaries point confidence interval (ci_low ci_up output). argument domain determines whether average calculated within individual time points (curves) - domain = "time" sensors (topographic maps) - domain = "space".
code: # preparing data for later visualisation  # filtering signal without outlier epochs 14 and 15 # and computing epoch level jackknife average from baseline corrected data # Note: data filtering is possible both using the pick_data() function or dplyr commands edata <- epochdata |>   pick_data(subject_rg = 2, epoch_rg = 1:13) |>   baseline_correction(baseline_range = 1:10)  s1 <- edata |>   dplyr::filter(time == 10) |>   compute_mean(amplitude = "signal_base", level = "epoch",                domain = "space", type = "jack")

title: diegr
text: interactive_waveforms() plot_time_mean() can used display time course signal. function interactive_waveforms() interactively displays individual waveforms different levels via plotly, function plot_time_mean() adapted directly display average signal including pointwise confidence interval ggplot object.
code: # computing jackknife average from channel E65  s2 <- edata |>   pick_data(sensor_rg = "E65") |>   compute_mean(amplitude = "signal_base", level = "epoch",                domain = "time", type = "jack")  # plotting the average, the zero time point (stimulus) is set to 10 plot_time_mean(s2, t0 = 10)

title: diegr
text: original electrode grid coarse graphical rendering. achieve smoother visually appealing results plots, ’s necessary generate denser mesh points. refined mesh provides better spatial resolution enhances quality visualizations. Creating new mesh available point_mesh() function. function computes coordinates mesh 2D /3D enables control density (argument n) shape (argument type) result mesh. default setting creates polygonal mesh starting number 10000 points computes coordinates dimensions, available $D2 $D3 parts result list (class "mesh"). simple created mesh plotting use function plot_point_mesh(), results two dimensional ggplot point mesh three dimensional rgl plot depending input dimension. Notes: Creating plotting mesh subset whole template montage available sensor_select parameter. consistency created mesh plot use vector sensor labels functions. input plot_point_mesh() must relevant part coordinates - $D2 two dimensional $D3 three dimensional plot. number mesh points large, longer visible plot mesh looks like solid surface (can seen first plot). Depending hardware used, computational cost default n = 10000 can high. case recommend reduce n reuse precomputed mesh across plots speed.  diegr’s plotting functions also allow users input custom mesh created way, necessary maintain structure following "mesh" object. mesh input specified, graphic functions automatically use mesh created point_mesh() default settings.
code: # creating a mesh with default settings sensors204 <- unique(epochdata$sensor) M1 <- point_mesh(template = "HCGSN256", sensor_select = sensors204) # plot output in 2D plot_point_mesh(M1$D2, sensor_select = sensors204)  # creating a circular mesh, only 2D coordinates M2 <- point_mesh(dimension = 2, n = 3000, template = "HCGSN256",                  sensor_select = sensors204, type = "circle") # plotting a mesh - function allows different options of the result plot plot_point_mesh(M2$D2, sensor_select = sensors204, col_sensors = "purple",                 label_sensors = TRUE, cex = 0.1)

title: diegr
text: topo_plot() function used plot topographic map brain signal, amplitude values colored default using topographic colour scale. alternative function adapted directly plot mean along confidence interval bounds plot_topo_mean(). default topographic colour scale, amplitude = 0 mapped blue–green boundary; positive values trend towards yellow/red, negative towards dark blue. coulour_scale() function also offers "redblue" palette, negative values corresponding shades blue positive values corresponding shades red. Additionally, users can choose palettes using col_scale argument. topo_ functions allow setting optionally arguments editing output appearance (without contours, sensor names, etc.) return ggplot object customization. Notes: input values amplitude (also CI bounds case plot_topo_mean() function) outside chosen col_range cause “holes” resulting plot. compare results different subjects conditions, setting values col_range col_scale arguments cases necessary.
code: # Plot average topographic map of baseline corrected signal for subject 1  # from the time point 10 (the time of the stimulus) # the outlier epoch 14 is extracted before computing average  # preparing data data_base <- epochdata |>   pick_data(subject_rg = 1, time_rg = 1:10) |>   baseline_correction(baseline_range = 1:10)  data_mean <- data_base |>   pick_data(epoch_rg = 1:13, time_rg = 10) |>   compute_mean(amplitude = "signal_base", type = "point",                domain = "space")  # plotting the base topographic polygon map with contours and legend # interval (-30,15) is selected in consideration of the signal progress topo_plot(data = data_mean, amplitude = "average",            col_range = c(-30, 15), contour = TRUE)  # plotting the same map without contours and legend  # but with sensor labels and adding the title g1 <- topo_plot(data = data_mean, amplitude = "average",                 col_range = c(-30, 15),                 label_sensors = TRUE, show_legend = FALSE) g1 + ggplot2::ggtitle("Subject 1, time of the stimulus")  # plotting the average together with CI bounds using plot_topo_mean plot_topo_mean(data = data_mean, template = "HCGSN256", col_range = c(-30, 15))

title: diegr
text: scalp_plot() function created plotting scalp polygon map EEG signal amplitude using default topographic colour scale topo_plot()). result plot rendered using rgl::shape3d function signal interpolation sensor locations based thin-plate spline interpolation model. Correct mesh triangulation required appropriate colour rendering. triangulation constructed make_triangulation(), creates Delaunay type-triangulation (Lai & Schumaker, 2007) consistently oriented edges (Schneider & Eberly, 2003). Note: - input values amplitude outside chosen col_range cause “holes” resulting plot. - obtain comparable results different subjects conditions, setting values col_range col_scale arguments cases necessary. rgl output enables zoom rotate image default view back head.
code: # plotting the scalp polygon map of previously prepared signal s1 #open3d() scalp_plot(s1, amplitude = "average", col_range = c(-30, 15))  # note: the output is not plotted to reduce the vignette file size

title: diegr
text: package includes animate_topo() animate_topo_mean() function 2D topographic animation time animate_scalp() function 3D scalp animation time. functions allow export output, gif animation using gifski package 2D case .mp4 video format using av package 3D case. topographic map animation uses gganimate accepts additional parameters passed gganimate::animate() via .... input parameters animate_topo() topo_plot() function, parameters related animation properties export added also t_lim parameter setting length timeline displayed animation. animate_topo_mean() function customized topographic maps average signal together pointwise confidence interval bounds displayed topographic maps sides average map. Usage almost identical animate_topo() function, input data must contain columns average, ci_up ci_low (like output compute_mean function). Example: animation time course EEG signal subject 1 epoch 5 (epochdata) time points 10 20 whole range time 0:50 created follows (output rendered reduce vignette file size): scalp animation enables export video .mp4 format using av package save sequence frames chosen directory setting frames_dir parameter. animation speed can controlled sec parameter viewer framerate parameter exported video. video resolution quality can affected using par3d function, example rgl::par3d(windowRect = c(100, 100, 800, 800)). Example scalp animation data (output rendered reduce vignette file size): interested animation rotating scalp visualization fixed time point, can easily achieve using combination rgl::play3d rgl::spin3d functions according following code.
code: # filtering the example data  s1e05 <- epochdata |>    pick_data(subject_rg = 1, epoch_rg = 5, time_rg = 10:20)  # Plot animation with setting the range of time and t0 = 10 indicating the time of the stimulus: animate_topo(s1e05, amplitude = "signal", t_lim = c(0,50), t0 = 10)  # Export the gif animation - this code will create the animation inside your working directory. # If you want to export it elsewhere, set the whole path in output_path parameter. animate_topo(s1e05, amplitude = "signal", t_lim = c(0,50),              t0 = 10, output_path = "example_animation.gif") # Plot animation with default mesh and triangulation: animate_scalp(s1e05, amplitude = "signal") # export the video - the .mp4 extension is required for correct functioning rgl::par3d(windowRect = c(100, 100, 800, 800)) animate_scalp(s1e05, amplitude = "signal",                frames_dir = "your_frames_dir_path",                output_path = "your_created_video_path.mp4") #open3d() scalp_plot(s1, amplitude = "average", col_range = c(-30,15)) rgl::play3d(rgl::spin3d(axis = c(0, 0, 1), rpm = 10), duration = 10)  # note: the output is not plotted to reduce the vignette file size

what: Step-by-step example: Comparing Topographic Maps of Two Subjects
title: diegr
text: section present sample code analyzing topographic maps across subjects: Outliers detection Subject 1: epoch 14 obvious outlier. Subject 2: epoch 15 obvious outlier, epoch 14 denoted outlier 37 time points - exclude analysis. Baseline correction exclude outlier epochs baseline correction, otherwise affect baseline average computing. Note: multiple subjects (variables) input data, baseline_correction() add grouping structure, baseline calculation provided separately unique combinations variables. procedure allows compute baseline correction subjects one step. Average computing compute average topographic map time point 35 (100 ms stimulus) subjects. use standard (un-weighted) pointwise average bootstrap confidence intervals. Average plotting maintain consistency subjects, first construct mesh set colour range use figures: plotting, use plot_topo_mean() function, directly adapted rendering topographic map average EEG amplitude together lower upper confidence interval (CI) bounds. Average difference plot display difference average subjects considered example, can also use red-blue colour palette inside topo_plot() function.
code: # using IQR method for selected sensor from central region  dataE59 <- epochdata |>   pick_data(sensor_rg = "E59") outliers_epoch(dataE59, method = "iqr")  # verify results by visual inspection (for each subject separately) dataE59 |>   dplyr::filter(subject == 1) |>   interactive_waveforms(amplitude = "signal", level = "epoch",                         t0 = 10) dataE59 |>   dplyr::filter(subject == 2) |>   interactive_waveforms(amplitude = "signal", level = "epoch",                         t0 = 10) subjects_base <- epochdata |>   pick_data(epoch_rg = 1:13) |>   baseline_correction(baseline_range = 1:10) subjects_mean <- subjects_base |>   dplyr::filter(time == 35) |>   compute_mean(amplitude = "signal_base", domain = "space",                level = "epoch", R = 1000) # prepare a mesh for plotting M <- point_mesh(dimension = 2, n = 4000, template = "HCGSN256",                 sensor_select = unique(subjects_mean$sensor),                 type = "polygon") # compute consistent col_range across subjects # a) find the range of average amplitude range(subjects_mean$average)  #> [1] -15.634288   8.609518 # -15.634288   8.609518 # b) make the range symmetric cr_subjects <- c(-16,16) # plot the average topographic maps with the same color range for both subjects subjects_mean |>   dplyr::filter(subject == 1) |>   plot_topo_mean(mesh = M, template = "HCGSN256",                  col_range = cr_subjects, contour = TRUE)  subjects_mean |>   dplyr::filter(subject == 2) |>   plot_topo_mean(mesh = M, template = "HCGSN256",                  col_range = cr_subjects, contour = TRUE)  # note: the output is not plotted to reduce the vignette file size # compute difference subjects_diff <- subjects_mean |>   dplyr::group_by(.data$sensor) |>   dplyr::reframe(     diff = .data$average[.data$subject == "1"] - .data$average[.data$subject == "2"]   ) # create colour scale CS1 <- create_scale(col_range = range(subjects_diff$diff), type = "redblue") # display the plot: positive difference values (i.e., average for subject 1 higher than for subject 2) # are displayed in shades of red, negative values in shades of blue topo_plot(subjects_diff, amplitude = "diff", mesh = M,           template = "HCGSN256", col_scale = CS1)

title: Dynamic and Interactive EEG Graphics
text: name diegr comes Dynamic Interactive EEG Graphics using R. diegr package enables researchers visualize high-density electroencephalography (HD-EEG) data animated interactive graphics, supporting exploratory confirmatory analyses sensor-level brain signals. package diegr includes: interactive boxplots (boxplot_epoch, boxplot_subject, boxplot_rt) interactive waveforms (interactive_waveforms) topographic maps 2D (topo_plot) scalp plots 3D (scalp_plot) functions computing summary statistics, baseline correction, pointwise jackknife mean (summary_stats_rt,baseline_correction, compute_mean) functions easy selection subdata region interest (pick_data, pick_region) functions plotting mean pointwise confidence interval (plot_time_mean, plot_topo_mean) animations time course raw signal average 2D 3D (animate_topo, animate_topo_mean, animate_scalp)

title: Dynamic and Interactive EEG Graphics
text: large volumes data obtained HD-EEG measurements, package allows users work directly database tables (addition common formats data frames tibbles). procedure efficient terms memory usage. database want use input diegr functions must contain columns following structure: group - ID groups, subject - ID subjects, sensor - sensor labels, epoch - epoch numbers, condition - labels experimental condition, time - numbers time points (sampling points, ms), signal - EEG signal amplitude microvolts (functions possible set name column containing amplitude arbitrarily). Note: necessary data contain variables, , must named according structure presented . package contains included training datasets: epochdata: epoched HD-EEG data (anonymized short slice big HD-EEG study presented Madetko-Alster, 2025) 2 subjects 204 selected sensors 50 time points, HCGSN256: list Cartesian coordinates HD-EEG sensor positions 3D space scalp surface projection 2D space rtdata: response times (time stimulus presentation pressing button) experiment involving simple visual motor task (anonymized short slice big HD-EEG study presented Madetko-Alster, 2025). information structure built-data see package vignette vignette("diegr", package = "diegr").

what: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
title: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
text: Calculate pointwise jackknife (leave-one-) average signal across temporal spatial domain together standard error pointwise confidence interval (CI) bounds. Pointwise averages can computed two ways: standard (un-weighted) default, weighted using values column specified weights_col. function computes average group, subject, sensor/time point, condition epoch level (according level parameter). option level = "epoch" epochs averaged etc. Function assumes pre-prepared data according chosen level.

title: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
code: compute_mean(   data,   amplitude = "signal_base",   domain = c("time", "space"),   level = c("epoch", "condition", "sensor", "subject", "group"),   type = c("point", "jack"),   weights_col = NULL,   R = NULL,   alpha = 0.95 )

title: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
text: data data frame, tibble database table input data, required columns: time sensor (according selected domain), column EEG amplitude specified argument amplitude columns corresponding selected level. amplitude character specifying name column input data EEG amplitude values. Default "signal_base" computing average baseline corrected signal. domain character specifying domain average computed. One "time" "space". Option "time" computes time-resolved average time point, whereas "space" computes space-resolved average sensor. level character specifying level average calculation. possible values "epoch","condition", "sensor", "subject" "group". See Details information. type character specifying method calculating average, "point" pointwise average "jack" jackknife leave-one-average. weights_col character specifying name column containing observation weights. NULL, un-weighted standard pointwise average computed. R number replications used bootstrap interval calculation. Required computing pointwise mean. Default value 1000. alpha number indicating confidence interval level. default value 0.95 95% confidence intervals.

title: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
text: tibble resulting average CI bounds according chosen level, domain alpha arguments. statistics saved columns average computed average amplitude value, n number observations used average computing, se standard error mean, ci_low lower bound confidence interval ci_up upper bound confidence interval.

title: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
text: function supports averaging different hierarchical levels data (using level argument): "epoch": averaging across epochs. Returns average curve (time domain) sensor array (space domain) combination grouping variables. "condition": averages across experimental conditions. "sensor": averages across sensors (space domain) time points (time domain). "subject": averages across subjects. "group": averages across groups subjects (highest aggregation level). function assumes input adapted desired level averaging (.e. epoch level epoch column must present data etc.). levels higher epochs, averages lower level assumed input data. Weighted vs un-weighted average (type = "point"): weights_col NULL, observation treated equally (weight = 1), producing standard un-weighted mean, standard errors (SE), CI. weight_cols provided, weighted average computed using values specified column weights. SE CI computed based weighted variance. Computing standard error mean: type = "point", standard error computed sample standard deviation divided square root sample size standard mean weighted alternative (weights_col specified). type = "jack", standard error jackknife standard error mean (exact formula see Efron Tibshirani 1994). Computing point confidence intervals: average value, upper lower bounds point confidence interval also available. Setting type = "point" R: bounds computed using percentile method bootstrapping R replicates (can slow large amounts data). Setting type = "point" without specifying R: bounds computed using standard error mean approximation Student distribution. Setting type = "jack": bounds computed using jackknife standard error mean approximation Student t-distribution. Note: used method assumes equal variance symmetric distribution, may problematic small samples. Note: NA's amplitude weights_col columns, corresponding rows ignored average calculation function prints warning message.

title: Calculate mean in temporal or spatial domain — compute_mean
text: Efron B., Tibshirani RJ. Introduction Bootstrap. Chapman & Hall/CRC; 1994.

code: # Create red-blue scale on interval (-10,10) with default step number create_scale(col_range = c(-10,10), type = "redblue") #> $colors #>  [1] "#2E5A87" "#5A7EA2" "#86A3BE" "#B2C8DA" "#DFEDF6" "#E4CCC6" "#D59CA2" #>  [8] "#C66C7F" "#B73C5B" "#A90C38" #>  #> $breaks #>  [1] -10  -8  -6  -4  -2   0   2   4   6   8  10 #>   # Create topographic scale on interval c(-5,10) with small k (finer division) CStopo <- create_scale(col_range = c(-5, 10), k = 0.02) # plot colours of the scale as points k_col <- length(CStopo$colors) plot(1:k_col, rep(1, k_col), col = CStopo$colors, pch = 16,  axes = FALSE, ylab = "", xlab = "")

title: Example high-density (HD-EEG) epoched data — epochdata
text: dataset short slice HD-EEG dataset study investigating impact deep brain stimulation patients advanced Parkinson's disease (Madetko-Alster, 2025). experiment subjects performed simple visual motor task (pressing response button case target visual stimulus presentation). data measured 256-channel HydroCel Geodesic Sensor Net sampling frequency 250 Hz. study carried Central European Institute Technology Brno supported Czech Health Research Council AZV NU21-04-00445. Example dataset contains amplitude values measured chosen 204 channels 50 time points (stimulus time point 10) 2 representative subjects (one patient one healthy control subject). total number 50 epochs subject, 14 (15) epochs selected sample dataset. data intended testing EEG preprocessing visualization methods.

title: Example high-density (HD-EEG) epoched data — epochdata
code: data("epochdata")

title: Example high-density (HD-EEG) epoched data — epochdata
text: data frame consist 295 800 rows (50 time points x 204 sensors x 29 epochs) five columns: time Number time point. Time point 10 corresponds stimulus onset (0 ms) interval two time points corresponds time period 4 ms. signal HD-EEG signal amplitude, microvolts. epoch Factor variable epoch number, 14 epochs subject 1, 15 epochs subject 2. sensor Sensor label, according labeling used EGI Geodesic Sensor Net Technical Manual. subject Factor variable subject ID, 1 - representative healthy control subject, 2 - representative patient subject.

title: Example high-density (HD-EEG) epoched data — epochdata
text: Central European Institute Technology, Masaryk University, Brno, Czech Republic.

title: Example high-density (HD-EEG) epoched data — epochdata
text: EGI Geodesic Sensor Net Technical Manual (2024) https://www.egi.com/knowledge-center Madetko-Alster N., Alster P., Lamoš M., Šmahovská L., Boušek T., Rektor . Bočková M. role somatosensory cortex self-paced movement impairment Parkinson’s disease. Clinical Neurophysiology. 2025, vol. 171, 11-17.

title: Example high-density (HD-EEG) epoched data — epochdata
Plot interactive waveform graph — interactive_waveforms
text: Function plotting time series EEG signal colour-coded epoch, condition, channel, subject group (depending selected level parameter) interactive plotly graph. function assumes input data already filtered desired subset according level. using function plotting average, option add confidence band using CI argument. output plotly format enables easily edit image layout.

title: Plot interactive waveform graph — interactive_waveforms
code: interactive_waveforms(   data,   amplitude = "signal",   FS = 250,   t0 = NULL,   col_palette,   level = "epoch",   avg = TRUE,   CI = FALSE,   use_latex = TRUE )

title: Plot interactive waveform graph — interactive_waveforms
text: data data frame, tibble database table input data containing time column columns corresponding selected amplitude level parameter (see Details). amplitude character specifying name column input data EEG amplitude values. Default "signal". FS sampling frequency. Default value 250 Hz. t0 Index zero time point, .e. point, 0 ms marked (often time stimulus time response). col_palette Optionally, colour palette plotting lines. missing, rainbow palette used. expected length (higher) number unique levels (e.g. number epochs level = "epoch"). level character specifying level time curves. possible values "epoch" (default option), "condition", "sensor", "subject" "group". See details information. avg logical value indicating, average black curve plotted. Default TRUE. CI logical value indicating, confidence ribbon plotted. Default FALSE. See Details information. use_latex logical value indicating whether use LaTeX formatting y-axis title. default TRUE.

title: Plot interactive waveform graph — interactive_waveforms
text: plotly object showing interactive time series signal according chosen level.

title: Plot interactive waveform graph — interactive_waveforms
text: input data frame database table must contain column time (column time point numbers) column EEG amplitude (average amplitude) specified argument amplitude. must also contain least one optional columns (according level parameter - "sensor" level column sensor required etc.):group - column group identifiers,subject - column subject IDs,sensor - column sensor labels,epoch - column epoch numbers. Note: average signals must pre-aggregated plotting higher grouping levels, example sensor level assumes mean sensor signal amplitude column (input data individual epochs together sensor level setting result mess output). Plotting confidence ribbon: plot confidence bands around average lines (CI = TRUE), input data must include ci_up ci_low columns (output tibble compute_mean function).

title: Plot interactive waveform graph — interactive_waveforms

what: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
text: Function creating Delaunay type-triangulation (see Schumaker 2007) consistent oriented edges adapted regular point mesh created point_mesh function. See Details information.

title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
code: make_triangulation(mesh)

title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
text: mesh data frame tibble named columns: x, y (required) index (optionally, missing, generated internally). optimally D2 element "mesh" object list structure uniformly spaced grid.

title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
text: three column matrix indices vertices triangles. row represents one triangle, defined three vertex indices pointing rows input mesh.

title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
text: type-Delaunay triangulation triangulation obtained drawing north-east diagonals subrectangles triangulated area. Due regularity input mesh (sense distances mesh points), simplified procedure used: triangulation created within individual strips bound together. order vertices chosen maintain consistent orientation triangles (details see Schneider 2003). input mesh regular grid spacing, result triangulation may meaningful meet Delaunay triangulation criteria.

title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
text: Lai M-J, Schumaker LL. Spline functions triangulations. Cambridge University Press; 2007. Schneider PJ, Eberly DH. Geometric Tools Computer Graphics. Morgan Kaufmann Series Computer Graphics. San Francisco: Morgan Kaufmann, 2003.

title: Make triangulation of 2D point mesh — make_triangulation
text: 3D plot
code:
# a) Create small mesh for triangulation example # using 204 electrodes from epochdata M <- point_mesh(n = 500, template = "HCGSN256", sensor_select = unique(epochdata$sensor))  # b) Make triangulation on this mesh TRI <- make_triangulation(M$D2) head(TRI) #>      [,1] [,2] [,3] #> [1,]    1   16   15 #> [2,]    1    2   16 #> [3,]    2   17   16 #> [4,]    2    3   17 #> [5,]    3   18   17 #> [6,]    3    4   18  # c) plot triangulation in 2D # prepare empty plot plot(M$D2, type = "n", main = "Triangulation plot", xlab = "", ylab = "", asp = 1, axes = FALSE) # create a structure for plotting x0 <- c() y0 <- c() x1 <- c() y1 <- c() for (i in 1:nrow(TRI)) {   v_indices <- TRI[i, ]   v_coords <- M$D2[v_indices, ]   x0 <- c(x0, v_coords[1, "x"], v_coords[2, "x"], v_coords[3, "x"])   y0 <- c(y0, v_coords[1, "y"], v_coords[2, "y"], v_coords[3, "y"])   x1 <- c(x1, v_coords[2, "x"], v_coords[3, "x"], v_coords[1, "x"])   y1 <- c(y1, v_coords[2, "y"], v_coords[3, "y"], v_coords[1, "y"])  } # plot triangulation using segments segments(x0, y0, x1, y1)   ## Note: this code opens a rgl 3D viewer # d) Plot the result triangulation as 3D wire model using rgl  rgl::open3d()  rgl::wire3d(rgl::mesh3d(M$D3$x, M$D3$y, M$D3$z, triangles = t(TRI))) 3D plot #ifdef TEXTURE_luminance_alpha
    float luminance = dot(vec3(1.,1.,1.),textureColor.rgb)/3.;

#if defined(TEXMODE_replace) || defined(TEXMODE_decal)
    textureColor = vec4(luminance, luminance, luminance, textureColor.a);
#endif 

#ifdef TEXMODE_modulate
    textureColor = vec4(luminance*lighteffect.rgb, 
                        textureColor.a*lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_blend
    textureColor = vec4((1. - luminance)*lighteffect.rgb,
                        textureColor.a*lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_add
    textureColor = vec4(luminance + lighteffect.rgb, 
                        textureColor.a*lighteffect.a);

#endif

#endif // TEXTURE_luminance_alpha
    
    fragColor = textureColor;

#elif defined(IS_TEXT)
    if (textureColor.a < 0.1)
      discard;
    else
      fragColor = textureColor;
#else
    fragColor = lighteffect;
#endif // HAS_TEXTURE
    
#ifdef HAS_FOG
    // uFogParms elements: x = near, y = far, z = fogscale, w = (1-sin(FOV/2))/(1+sin(FOV/2))
    // In Exp and Exp2: use density = density/far
    // fogF will be the proportion of fog
    // Initialize it to the linear value
    float fogF;
    if (uFogMode > 0) {
      fogF = (uFogParms.y - vPosition.z/vPosition.w)/(uFogParms.y - uFogParms.x);
      if (uFogMode > 1)
        fogF = mix(uFogParms.w, 1.0, fogF);
      fogF = fogF*uFogParms.z;
      if (uFogMode == 2)
        fogF = 1.0 - exp(-fogF);
      // Docs are wrong: use (density*c)^2, not density*c^2
      // https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/mesa/mesa/-/blob/master/src/mesa/swrast/s_fog.c#L58
      else if (uFogMode == 3)
        fogF = 1.0 - exp(-fogF*fogF);
      fogF = clamp(fogF, 0.0, 1.0);
      gl_FragColor = vec4(mix(fragColor.rgb, uFogColor, fogF), fragColor.a);
    } else gl_FragColor = fragColor;
#else
    gl_FragColor = fragColor;
#endif // HAS_FOG
    
}","players":[],"webGLoptions":{"preserveDrawingBuffer":true},"fastTransparency":true},"evals":[],"jsHooks":[]}

title: Select outlier epochs — outliers_epoch
text: Function identifies epochs outlier values numeric EEG amplitude variable chosen time points. Outliers detected separately time point within groups present data. function summarizes many times epoch marked outlier across time points. Epochs marked outliers based one following criteria: interquartile range criterion, percentile approach Hampel filter method.

title: Select outlier epochs — outliers_epoch
code: outliers_epoch(   data,   amplitude = "signal",   time = NULL,   method = c("iqr", "percentile", "hampel"),   k_iqr = 1.5,   k_mad = 3,   p = 0.975,   print_tab = TRUE )

title: Select outlier epochs — outliers_epoch
text: data data frame, tibble database table input data, required columns: time, epoch column EEG amplitude specified amplitude parameter. Optional columns: group, subject, sensor, condition. amplitude character specifying name column input data EEG amplitude values. Default "signal". time vector time range outliers detection. defined, outliers searched time points dataset. method character denoting method used outlier detection. options : "iqr" interquartile range (IQR) criterion (default value), "percentile" percentile method "hampel" Hampel filter method. See details information methods. k_iqr positive numeric value denoting scaling factor used IQR criterion. Default value k_iqr = 1.5. k_mad positive numeric value denoting scaling factor used Hampel filter method. Default value k_mad = 3. p probability value [0,1] interval determining percentile percentile method (according probs argument quantile() function). default value set 0.975 interval formed 2.5 97.5 percentiles. print_tab Logical. Indicates, whether result table printed console. Default TRUE.

title: Select outlier epochs — outliers_epoch
text: list following components: epoch_table data frame epoch ID number time points epoch evaluated outlier. (epochs occurrence outliers least one time point included.) outliers_data data frame subset data corresponding outliers found. (full record flagged point epoch_table.) setting print_tab = TRUE, epoch_table also printed console.

title: Select outlier epochs — outliers_epoch
text: input data frame database table must contain least following columns: epoch - column epoch numbers/labels, time - column time point numbers, signal (name specified amplitude parameter) - column measured EEG signal values. outlier detection method chosen method argument. possibilities iqr: interquartile range criterion, values outside interval [lower quartile - k_iqr * IQR, upper quartile + k_iqr * IQR] considered outliers. IQR denotes interquartile range k_iqr scaling factor. percentile: percentile method, values outside interval defined chosen percentiles considered outliers. Note: chosing small pleads marking many () values. hampel: Hampel filter method, values outside interval [median - k_mad * MAD, median + k_mad * MAD] considered outliers. MAD denotes median absolute deviation k_mad scaling factor. methods operates independently per time point, globally across time. Note: large datasets, calculation can time-consuming. recommended pre-filter subset data using function reduce computation time.

code: scalp_plot(   data,   amplitude,   mesh,   tri = NULL,   coords = NULL,   template = NULL,   col_range = NULL,   col_scale = NULL,   view )

title: Plot scalp map of EEG signal — scalp_plot
text: data data frame, tibble database table input data plot least two columns: sensor sensor labels column EEG amplitude specified argument amplitude. amplitude character specifying name column input data EEG amplitude values. mesh object class "mesh" (named list structure) used computing IM model. defined, polygon point mesh default settings point_mesh function used. See details information structure. tri three column matrix indices vertices triangles. row represents one triangle, defined three vertex indices. missing, triangulation computed using make_triangulation function D2 element mesh. coords Sensor coordinates tibble data frame named x, y, z sensor columns. sensor labels must match labels sensor column data. defined, HCGSN256 template used. template kind sensor template montage used. Currently available option "HCGSN256" denoting 256-channel HydroCel Geodesic Sensor Net v.1.0, also default setting. col_range vector minimum maximum value amplitude used colour palette plotting. defined, range interpolated signal used. col_scale Optionally, colour scale use plotting. defined, computed col_range. view character creating temporary rotated scene (according neurological terminology). Possible values : "superior", "anterior", "posterior", "left", "right". missing, default view according user settings displayed. Note: Input coordinates corresponding positions HCGSN template required obtain appropriate view.

title: Plot scalp map of EEG signal — scalp_plot
text: 3D scalp map rendered via rgl::shade3d() interactive window.

title: Plot scalp map of EEG signal — scalp_plot
text: parameter mesh optimally "mesh" object (output point_mesh function) list structure: D2	data frame x y columns D3 data frame x, y z columns. See point_mesh information. case, setting argument tri optional, absent, triangulation based D2 element mesh calculated used plot. input mesh contains 3D coordinates point mesh D3 element, use previously created triangulation (tri argument) necessary. compare results 2D topographical plot 3D scalp plot use mesh cases. careful choosing argument col_range. amplitude input data contains values outside chosen range, cause "holes" resulting plot. compare results different subjects conditions, set values col_range col_scale arguments cases. default used scale based topographical colours zero value always border blue green shades. Notes: function focuses visualization perform data subsetting. Users expected filter data beforehand using standard dplyr verbs pick_data function. correct rendering plot, function requires openGL-capable device. Displaying rotated scalp map using view argument requires previous call open3d(). specifying coords template time, template parameter takes precedence coords parameter ignored.

# \donttest{ ## Note: The example opens a rgl 3D viewer. # Plot average scalp map of signal for subject 2 from the time point 10 (the time of the stimulus) # the outliers (epoch 14 and 15) are extracted before computing  # a) preparing data edata <- pick_data(epochdata, subject_rg = 2, epoch_rg = 1:13, time_rg = 1:10) # a2) baseline correction (needed for suitable topographic map) data_base <- baseline_correction(edata, baseline_range = 1:10) # a3) average computing data_mean <- data_base |> dplyr::filter(time == 10) |> compute_mean(amplitude = "signal_base", type = "point", domain = "space")  # b) plotting the scalp polygon map scalp_plot(data_mean, amplitude = "average", col_range = c(-30, 15)) 3D plot // File 1 is the vertex shader
#ifdef GL_ES
#ifdef GL_FRAGMENT_PRECISION_HIGH
precision highp float;
#else
precision mediump float;
#endif
#endif

attribute vec3 aPos;
attribute vec4 aCol;
uniform mat4 mvMatrix;
uniform mat4 prMatrix;
varying vec4 vCol;
varying vec4 vPosition;

#ifdef NEEDS_VNORMAL
attribute vec3 aNorm;
uniform mat4 normMatrix;
varying vec4 vNormal;
#endif

#if defined(HAS_TEXTURE) || defined (IS_TEXT)
attribute vec2 aTexcoord;
varying vec2 vTexcoord;
#endif

#ifdef FIXED_SIZE
uniform vec3 textScale;
#endif

#ifdef FIXED_QUADS
attribute vec3 aOfs;
#endif

#ifdef IS_TWOSIDED
#ifdef HAS_NORMALS
varying float normz;
uniform mat4 invPrMatrix;
#else
attribute vec3 aPos1;
attribute vec3 aPos2;
varying float normz;
#endif
#endif // IS_TWOSIDED

#ifdef FAT_LINES
attribute vec3 aNext;
attribute vec2 aPoint;
varying vec2 vPoint;
varying float vLength;
uniform float uAspect;
uniform float uLwd;
#endif

#ifdef USE_ENVMAP
varying vec3 vReflection;
#endif

void main(void) {
  
#ifndef IS_BRUSH
#if defined(NCLIPPLANES) || !defined(FIXED_QUADS) || defined(HAS_FOG) || defined(USE_ENVMAP)
  vPosition = mvMatrix * vec4(aPos, 1.);
#endif
  
#ifndef FIXED_QUADS
  gl_Position = prMatrix * vPosition;
#endif
#endif // !IS_BRUSH
  
#ifdef IS_POINTS
  gl_PointSize = POINTSIZE;
#endif
  
  vCol = aCol;
  
// USE_ENVMAP implies NEEDS_VNORMAL

#ifdef NEEDS_VNORMAL
  vNormal = normMatrix * vec4(-aNorm, dot(aNorm, aPos));
#endif

#ifdef USE_ENVMAP
  vReflection = normalize(reflect(vPosition.xyz/vPosition.w, 
                        normalize(vNormal.xyz/vNormal.w)));
#endif
  
#ifdef IS_TWOSIDED
#ifdef HAS_NORMALS
  /* normz should be calculated *after* projection */
  normz = (invPrMatrix*vNormal).z;
#else
  vec4 pos1 = prMatrix*(mvMatrix*vec4(aPos1, 1.));
  pos1 = pos1/pos1.w - gl_Position/gl_Position.w;
  vec4 pos2 = prMatrix*(mvMatrix*vec4(aPos2, 1.));
  pos2 = pos2/pos2.w - gl_Position/gl_Position.w;
  normz = pos1.x*pos2.y - pos1.y*pos2.x;
#endif
#endif // IS_TWOSIDED
  
#ifdef NEEDS_VNORMAL
  vNormal = vec4(normalize(vNormal.xyz), 1);
#endif
  
#if defined(HAS_TEXTURE) || defined(IS_TEXT)
  vTexcoord = aTexcoord;
#endif
  
#if defined(FIXED_SIZE) && !defined(ROTATING)
  vec4 pos = prMatrix * mvMatrix * vec4(aPos, 1.);
  pos = pos/pos.w;
  gl_Position = pos + vec4(aOfs*textScale, 0.);
#endif
  
#if defined(IS_SPRITES) && !defined(FIXED_SIZE)
  vec4 pos = mvMatrix * vec4(aPos, 1.);
  pos = pos/pos.w + vec4(aOfs,  0.);
  gl_Position = prMatrix*pos;
#endif
  
#ifdef FAT_LINES
  /* This code was inspired by Matt Deslauriers' code in 
   https://mattdesl.svbtle.com/drawing-lines-is-hard */
  vec2 aspectVec = vec2(uAspect, 1.0);
  mat4 projViewModel = prMatrix * mvMatrix;
  vec4 currentProjected = projViewModel * vec4(aPos, 1.0);
  currentProjected = currentProjected/currentProjected.w;
  vec4 nextProjected = projViewModel * vec4(aNext, 1.0);
  vec2 currentScreen = currentProjected.xy * aspectVec;
  vec2 nextScreen = (nextProjected.xy / nextProjected.w) * aspectVec;
  float len = uLwd;
  vec2 dir = vec2(1.0, 0.0);
  vPoint = aPoint;
  vLength = length(nextScreen - currentScreen)/2.0;
  vLength = vLength/(vLength + len);
  if (vLength > 0.0) {
    dir = normalize(nextScreen - currentScreen);
  }
  vec2 normal = vec2(-dir.y, dir.x);
  dir.x /= uAspect;
  normal.x /= uAspect;
  vec4 offset = vec4(len*(normal*aPoint.x*aPoint.y - dir), 0.0, 0.0);
  gl_Position = currentProjected + offset;
#endif
  
#ifdef IS_BRUSH
  gl_Position = vec4(aPos, 1.);
#endif

// File 2 is the fragment shader
#ifdef GL_ES
#ifdef GL_FRAGMENT_PRECISION_HIGH
precision highp float;
#else
precision mediump float;
#endif
#endif
varying vec4 vCol; // carries alpha
varying vec4 vPosition;
#if defined(HAS_TEXTURE) || defined (IS_TEXT)
varying vec2 vTexcoord;
uniform sampler2D uSampler;
#endif

#ifdef HAS_FOG
uniform int uFogMode;
uniform vec3 uFogColor;
uniform vec4 uFogParms;
#endif

#if defined(IS_LIT) && !defined(FIXED_QUADS)
varying vec4 vNormal;
#endif

#if NCLIPPLANES > 0
uniform vec4 vClipplane[NCLIPPLANES];
#endif

#if NLIGHTS > 0
uniform mat4 mvMatrix;
#endif

#ifdef IS_LIT
uniform vec3 emission;
uniform float shininess;
#if NLIGHTS > 0
uniform vec3 ambient[NLIGHTS];
uniform vec3 specular[NLIGHTS]; // light*material
uniform vec3 diffuse[NLIGHTS];
uniform vec3 lightDir[NLIGHTS];
uniform bool viewpoint[NLIGHTS];
uniform bool finite[NLIGHTS];
#endif
#endif // IS_LIT

#ifdef IS_TWOSIDED
uniform bool front;
varying float normz;
#endif

#ifdef FAT_LINES
varying vec2 vPoint;
varying float vLength;
#endif

#ifdef USE_ENVMAP
varying vec3 vReflection;
#endif

void main(void) {
  vec4 fragColor;
#ifdef FAT_LINES
  vec2 point = vPoint;
  bool neg = point.y < 0.0;
  point.y = neg ? (point.y + vLength)/(1.0 - vLength) :
                 -(point.y - vLength)/(1.0 - vLength);
#if defined(IS_TRANSPARENT) && defined(IS_LINESTRIP)
  if (neg && length(point) <= 1.0) discard;
#endif
  point.y = min(point.y, 0.0);
  if (length(point) > 1.0) discard;
#endif // FAT_LINES
  
#ifdef ROUND_POINTS
  vec2 coord = gl_PointCoord - vec2(0.5);
  if (length(coord) > 0.5) discard;
#endif
  
#if NCLIPPLANES > 0
  for (int i = 0; i < NCLIPPLANES; i++)
    if (dot(vPosition, vClipplane[i]) < 0.0) discard;
#endif
    
#ifdef FIXED_QUADS
    vec3 n = vec3(0., 0., 1.);
#elif defined(IS_LIT)
    vec3 n = normalize(vNormal.xyz);
#endif
    
#ifdef IS_TWOSIDED
    if ((normz <= 0.) != front) discard;
#endif

#ifdef IS_LIT
    vec3 eye = normalize(-vPosition.xyz/vPosition.w);
    vec3 lightdir;
    vec4 colDiff;
    vec3 halfVec;
    vec4 lighteffect = vec4(emission, 0.);
    vec3 col;
    float nDotL;
#ifdef FIXED_QUADS
    n = -faceforward(n, n, eye);
#endif
    
#if NLIGHTS > 0
    // Simulate two-sided lighting
    if (n.z < 0.0)
      n = -n;
    for (int i=0;i<NLIGHTS;i++) {
      colDiff = vec4(vCol.rgb * diffuse[i], vCol.a);
      lightdir = lightDir[i];
      if (!viewpoint[i]) {
        if (finite[i]) {
          lightdir = (mvMatrix * vec4(lightdir, 1.)).xyz;
        } else {
          lightdir = (mvMatrix * vec4(lightdir, 0.)).xyz;
        }
      }
      if (!finite[i]) {
        halfVec = normalize(lightdir + eye);
      } else {
        lightdir = normalize(lightdir - vPosition.xyz/vPosition.w);
        halfVec = normalize(lightdir + eye);
      }
      col = ambient[i];
      nDotL = dot(n, lightdir);
      col = col + max(nDotL, 0.) * colDiff.rgb;
      col = col + pow(max(dot(halfVec, n), 0.), shininess) * specular[i];
      lighteffect = lighteffect + vec4(col, colDiff.a);
    }
#endif
    
#else // not IS_LIT
    vec4 colDiff = vCol;
    vec4 lighteffect = colDiff;
#endif
    
#ifdef IS_TEXT
    vec4 textureColor = lighteffect*texture2D(uSampler, vTexcoord);
#endif
    
#ifdef HAS_TEXTURE

// These calculations use the definitions from 
// https://docs.gl/gl3/glTexEnv

#ifdef USE_ENVMAP
    float m = 2.0 * sqrt(dot(vReflection, vReflection) + 2.0*vReflection.z + 1.0);
    vec4 textureColor = texture2D(uSampler, vReflection.xy / m + vec2(0.5, 0.5));
#else
    vec4 textureColor = texture2D(uSampler, vTexcoord);
#endif

#ifdef TEXTURE_rgb

#if defined(TEXMODE_replace) || defined(TEXMODE_decal)
    textureColor = vec4(textureColor.rgb, lighteffect.a);
#endif 

#ifdef TEXMODE_modulate
    textureColor = lighteffect*vec4(textureColor.rgb, 1.);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_blend
    textureColor = vec4((1. - textureColor.rgb) * lighteffect.rgb, lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_add
    textureColor = vec4(lighteffect.rgb + textureColor.rgb, lighteffect.a);
#endif

#endif //TEXTURE_rgb
        
#ifdef TEXTURE_rgba

#ifdef TEXMODE_replace
// already done
#endif 

#ifdef TEXMODE_modulate
    textureColor = lighteffect*textureColor;
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_decal
    textureColor = vec4((1. - textureColor.a)*lighteffect.rgb) +
                     textureColor.a*textureColor.rgb, 
                     lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_blend
    textureColor = vec4((1. - textureColor.rgb) * lighteffect.rgb,
                    lighteffect.a*textureColor.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_add
    textureColor = vec4(lighteffect.rgb + textureColor.rgb,
                    lighteffect.a*textureColor.a);
#endif
    
#endif //TEXTURE_rgba
    
#ifdef TEXTURE_alpha
    float luminance = dot(vec3(1.,1.,1.),textureColor.rgb)/3.;

#if defined(TEXMODE_replace) || defined(TEXMODE_decal)
    textureColor = vec4(lighteffect.rgb, luminance);
#endif 

#if defined(TEXMODE_modulate) || defined(TEXMODE_blend) || defined(TEXMODE_add)
    textureColor = vec4(lighteffect.rgb, lighteffect.a*luminance);
#endif
 
#endif // TEXTURE_alpha
    
// The TEXTURE_luminance values are not from that reference    
#ifdef TEXTURE_luminance
    float luminance = dot(vec3(1.,1.,1.),textureColor.rgb)/3.;

#if defined(TEXMODE_replace) || defined(TEXMODE_decal)
    textureColor = vec4(luminance, luminance, luminance, lighteffect.a);
#endif 

#ifdef TEXMODE_modulate
    textureColor = vec4(luminance*lighteffect.rgb, lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_blend
    textureColor = vec4((1. - luminance)*lighteffect.rgb,
                        lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_add
    textureColor = vec4(luminance + lighteffect.rgb, lighteffect.a);
#endif

#endif // TEXTURE_luminance
 
    
#ifdef TEXTURE_luminance_alpha
    float luminance = dot(vec3(1.,1.,1.),textureColor.rgb)/3.;

#if defined(TEXMODE_replace) || defined(TEXMODE_decal)
    textureColor = vec4(luminance, luminance, luminance, textureColor.a);
#endif 

#ifdef TEXMODE_modulate
    textureColor = vec4(luminance*lighteffect.rgb, 
                        textureColor.a*lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_blend
    textureColor = vec4((1. - luminance)*lighteffect.rgb,
                        textureColor.a*lighteffect.a);
#endif

#ifdef TEXMODE_add
    textureColor = vec4(luminance + lighteffect.rgb, 
                        textureColor.a*lighteffect.a);

#endif

#endif // TEXTURE_luminance_alpha
    
    fragColor = textureColor;

#elif defined(IS_TEXT)
    if (textureColor.a < 0.1)
      discard;
    else
      fragColor = textureColor;
#else
    fragColor = lighteffect;
#endif // HAS_TEXTURE
    
#ifdef HAS_FOG
    // uFogParms elements: x = near, y = far, z = fogscale, w = (1-sin(FOV/2))/(1+sin(FOV/2))
    // In Exp and Exp2: use density = density/far
    // fogF will be the proportion of fog
    // Initialize it to the linear value
    float fogF;
    if (uFogMode > 0) {
      fogF = (uFogParms.y - vPosition.z/vPosition.w)/(uFogParms.y - uFogParms.x);
      if (uFogMode > 1)
        fogF = mix(uFogParms.w, 1.0, fogF);
      fogF = fogF*uFogParms.z;
      if (uFogMode == 2)
        fogF = 1.0 - exp(-fogF);
      // Docs are wrong: use (density*c)^2, not density*c^2
      // https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/mesa/mesa/-/blob/master/src/mesa/swrast/s_fog.c#L58
      else if (uFogMode == 3)
        fogF = 1.0 - exp(-fogF*fogF);
      fogF = clamp(fogF, 0.0, 1.0);
      gl_FragColor = vec4(mix(fragColor.rgb, uFogColor, fogF), fragColor.a);
    } else gl_FragColor = fragColor;
#else
    gl_FragColor = fragColor;
#endif // HAS_FOG

Summary statistics for rtdata # two different subjects, no group or conditions - results are computed per subject summary_stats_rt(rtdata) #> # A tibble: 2 × 7 #>   subject n_epoch min_rt max_rt median_rt avg_rt sd_rt #>   <fct>     <int>  <dbl>  <dbl>     <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> #> 1 1            14    166    270       194   198   26.1 #> 2 2            15    258    426       354   339.  44.1  # 2. Summary statistics for data with conditions # a) create example data data_cond <- rtdata data_cond$condition <- c(rep("a", 7), rep("b", 7), rep("a", 8), rep("b",7)) # b) compute statistics per subject and condition summary_stats_rt(data_cond) #> # A tibble: 4 × 8 #>   subject condition n_epoch min_rt max_rt median_rt avg_rt sd_rt #>   <fct>   <chr>       <int>  <dbl>  <dbl>     <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> #> 1 1       a               7    194    270       206   213.  26.9 #> 2 1       b               7    166    206       182   183.  14.1 #> 3 2       a               8    258    374       324   322   45.5 #> 4 2       b               7    314    426       358   359.  36.0 # c) compute statistics per conditions regardless of subjects # exclude "subject" column from computing summary_stats_rt(data_cond[,-1]) #> # A tibble: 2 × 7 #>   condition n_epoch min_rt max_rt median_rt avg_rt sd_rt #>   <chr>       <int>  <dbl>  <dbl>     <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> #> 1 a              15    194    374       270   271.  67.0 #> 2 b              14    166    426       260   271.  95.0

what: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
title: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
text: Plot topographic circle polygon map EEG signal amplitude using topographic colour scale. thin-plate spline interpolation model \(\text{IM:}\; \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}\) used signal interpolation sensor locations. output form ggplot object allows easily edit result image properties. function assumes input data already filtered desired subset (e.g., group, subject, time point).

title: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
code: topo_plot(   data,   amplitude,   mesh,   coords = NULL,   template = NULL,   col_range = NULL,   col_scale = NULL,   contour = FALSE,   show_legend = TRUE,   label_sensors = FALSE )

title: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
text: data data frame, tibble database table input data plot least two columns: sensor sensor labels column EEG amplitude specified argument amplitude. amplitude character string naming column EEG amplitude values. mesh "mesh" object (named list structure) containing least D2 element x y coordinates point mesh used computing IM model. defined, point mesh default settings point_mesh function used. coords Sensor coordinates tibble data frame named x, y sensor columns. sensor labels must match labels sensor column data. defined, HCGSN256 template used. template kind sensor template montage used. Currently available option "HCGSN256" denoting 256-channel HydroCel Geodesic Sensor Net v.1.0, also default setting. col_range vector minimum maximum value amplitude used colour palette plotting. defined, range interpolated signal used. col_scale Optionally, colour scale utilised plotting. list colors breaks components (usually created via create_scale). defined, computed col_range. contour Logical. Indicates, whether contours plotted graph. Default value FALSE. show_legend Logical. Indicates, whether legend displayed beside graph. Default value TRUE. label_sensors logical value indicating whether sensor labels also plotted. Default value FALSE.

title: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
text: ggplot object showing interpolated topographic map EEG amplitude.

title: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
text: details required mesh structure see point_mesh function. input mesh structure match format, error incorrect function behavior may occur. careful choosing argument col_range. amplitude input data contains values outside chosen range, cause "holes" resulting plot. compare results different subjects conditions, set values col_range col_scale arguments cases. default used scale based topographical colours zero value always border blue green shades. Notes: specifying coords template time, template parameter takes precedence coords parameter ignored. function focuses visualization perform data subsetting. Users expected filter data beforehand using standard dplyr verbs pick_data function.

title: Plot topographic map of EEG signal — topo_plot
code: # Plot average topographic map of signal for subject 2 from the time point 10 # (the time of the stimulus) without the outliers (epoch 14 and 15)  # a) preparing data # a1) extract required data edata <- pick_data(epochdata, subject_rg = 2, epoch_rg = 1:13, time_rg = 1:10) # a2) baseline correction (needed for suitable topographic map) data_base <- baseline_correction(edata, baseline_range = 1:10) # a3) average computing data_mean <- data_base |> dplyr::filter(time == 10) |> compute_mean(amplitude = "signal_base", type = "jack", domain = "space")   # b) plotting the topographic map with contours and legend # interval (-30,15) is selected in consideration of the signal progress topo_plot(data = data_mean, amplitude = "average", template = "HCGSN256", col_range = c(-30, 15), contour = TRUE)   # c) plotting the same map without contours but with sensor labels topo_plot(data = data_mean, amplitude = "average", template = "HCGSN256",  col_range = c(-30, 15), label_sensors = TRUE)
